    <router-outlet _ngcontent-serverapp-c4193883768=3D""></router-outlet><a=
pp-friedman><h1>Friedman Test</h1>
<a href=3D"https://numiqo.com/statistics-calculator/hypothesis-test/friedma=
n-test-calculator?example=3Dfriedman_test" target=3D"_blank" role=3D"button=
" class=3D"btn btn-primary mb-4">Medical example data</a>
<p>
  The Friedman test is a
  <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/parametric-and-non-parametric-tests" href=3D"h=
ttps://numiqo.com/tutorial/parametric-and-non-parametric-tests">non-paramet=
ric statistical test</a>
  used for analyzing repeated measures data. It is mainly used when the ass=
umptions of
  <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/test-of-normality" href=3D"https://numiqo.com/=
tutorial/test-of-normality">normality</a> and
  <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/levene-test" href=3D"https://numiqo.com/tutori=
al/levene-test">homogeneity of variances</a> are not met, making
  it a robust alternative to
  <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/anova-with-repeated-measures" href=3D"https://=
numiqo.com/tutorial/anova-with-repeated-measures">repeated measures ANOVA</=
a>.
</p>
<img alt=3D"Friedman-Test" title=3D"Friedman-Test" src=3D"https://numiqo.co=
m/assets/tutorial/Friedman/Friedman-Test.png">
<p>
  <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/dependent-and-independent-samples" href=3D"htt=
ps://numiqo.com/tutorial/dependent-and-independent-samples">What is a depen=
dent sample (repeated measure)?</a>
  In a dependent sample, the measured values are connected. For example, if=
 a sample is
  drawn of people who have knee surgery and these people are each surveyed =
before the
  surgery and one and two weeks after the surgery, it is a dependent sample=
. This is the
  case because the same person was interviewed at multiple time points.
</p>
<app-video-frame _nghost-serverapp-c2585983582=3D""><!---->
</app-video-frame>

<h2>Friedman Test vs. ANOVA with repeated measures</h2>
<p>
  You might rightly say that the
  <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/anova-with-repeated-measures" href=3D"https://=
numiqo.com/tutorial/anova-with-repeated-measures">analysis of variance with=
 repeated measures</a>
  tests exactly the same thing, since it also tests whether there is a diff=
erence between
  three or more dependent samples?
</p>

<p>
  That is correct, the Friedman test is the
  <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/parametric-and-non-parametric-tests" href=3D"h=
ttps://numiqo.com/tutorial/parametric-and-non-parametric-tests">non-paramet=
ric</a>
  counterpart of the analysis of variance with repeated measures. But what =
is the
  difference between the two tests?
</p>

<p>
  The analysis of variance tests the extent to which the measured values of=
 the dependent
  sample differ. The Friedman test, meanwhile, uses ranks rather than the a=
ctual measured
  values.
</p>
<img alt=3D"Friedman-Test-non-parametric" title=3D"Friedman-Test-non-parame=
tric" src=3D"https://numiqo.com/assets/tutorial/Friedman/Friedman-Test-non-=
parametric.png">
<p>
  The point in time where a person has the highest value gets rank 1, the p=
oint in time
  with the second highest value gets rank 2 and the point in time with the =
smallest value
  gets rank 3. This is now done for all persons or for all rows. Afterwards=
 the ranks of
  the single points of time are added up.
</p>

<p>
  At the first time we get a sum of 7, at the second time we get a sum of 8=
 and at the
  third time we get a sum of 9. Now we can check how much these rank sums d=
iffer.
</p>

<p>
  Why are ranks used? The big advantage is that if you don't look at the me=
an difference,
  but at the rank sum, the data doesn't have to be
  <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/test-of-normality" href=3D"https://numiqo.com/=
tutorial/test-of-normality">normally distributed</a>.
</p>

<p>
  Simplified, if your data are normally distributed, parametric tests are u=
sed. For more
  than two dependent samples, this is ANOVA with repeated measures.
</p>

<p>
  If your data are not normally distributed, non-parametric tests are used.=
 For more than
  two dependent samples, this is the Friedman test.
</p>

<h2>Hypotheses in the Friedman test</h2>
<p>
  This brings us to the research question, which you can answer with the Fr=
iedman test.
  The research question is, is there a significant difference between more =
than two
  dependent groups? The null and alternative hypothesis are therefore:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <b>Null hypothesis:</b> there is no significant difference between the =
dependent
    groups.
  </li>
  <li>
    <b> Alternative hypothesis: </b> there is a significant difference betw=
een the
    dependent groups.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  Of course, as already mentioned, the Friedman test does not use the true =
values, but the
  ranks.
</p>

<h2>Friedman test example</h2>
<a href=3D"https://numiqo.com/statistics-calculator/hypothesis-test/friedma=
n-test-calculator?example=3Dfriedman_test" target=3D"_blank" role=3D"button=
" class=3D"btn btn-primary mb-4">Medical example data</a>
<p>
  You might be interested to know whether therapy after a herniated disc ha=
s an influence
  on the patient's perception of pain. For this purpose, you measure the pa=
in sensation
  before the therapy, in the middle of the therapy and at the end of the th=
erapy. Now you
  want to know if there is a difference between the different time points.
</p>

<p>
  So, your independent variable is time, or the progress of the therapy ove=
r time. Your
  dependent variable is the perception of pain. You now have a progression =
of pain
  perception from each person over time and now you want to know if the the=
rapy has an
  effect on the pain perception.
</p>

<p>
  Put simply, in this one case the therapy has an influence and in this oth=
er case the
  therapy has no influence on the pain perception. In the course of time, t=
he pain
  perception does not change in this case, and it does in that other one.
</p>

<h2>Calculate Friedman test</h2>

<p>
  Let's say you want to investigate whether there is a difference in the re=
sponsiveness of
  people in the morning, at noon and in the evening. For this purpose, you =
measured the
  reactivity of 7 people in the morning, at noon and in the evening.
</p>

<p>
  In the first step we have to assign ranks to the values. For this we look=
 at each row
  separately.
</p>
<img alt=3D"calculate-Friedman-Test" title=3D"calculate-Friedman-Test" src=
=3D"https://numiqo.com/assets/tutorial/Friedman/calculate-Friedman-Test.png=
">

<p>
  In the first row, or in the first person, 45 is the largest value, this g=
ets rank 1,
  then comes 36 with rank 2 and 34 with rank 3. We now do the same for the =
second row.
  Here 36 is the largest value and gets rank 1, then comes 33 with rank 2 a=
nd 31 with rank
  3. We now do this for each row.
</p>

<p>
  Afterwards we can calculate the rank sum for each time of the day, so we =
simply sum up
  all ranks at each column. In the morning we get 17, at noon 11 and in the=
 evening 14.
</p>

<p>
  If there were no difference between the different time points in terms of=
 reaction time,
  we would expect the expected value at all time points. The expected value=
 is obtained
  with the first equation on the image and in this case it is 14. So if the=
re is no
  difference between morning noon and evening, we would actually expect a r=
ank sum of 14
  at all 3 time points.
</p>

<p>
  Next we can calculate the Chi<sup>2</sup> value, we get it with the secon=
d ecuation on
  the image. <i>N</i> is the number of persons, i.e. 7, <i>k</i> is the num=
ber of time
  points, i.e. 3 and the sum of <i>R<sup>2</sup></i> is 17<sup>2</sup> + 11=
<sup>2</sup> +
  14<sup>2</sup>. Thus we get a Chi<sup>2</sup> value of 2.57.
</p>

<p>
  Now we need the number of
  <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/degrees-of-freedom" href=3D"https://numiqo.com=
/tutorial/degrees-of-freedom">degrees of freedom</a>. This is given by
  the number of time points minus 1, so in our case 2.
</p>
<img alt=3D"Friedman-Test-p-Value" title=3D"Friedman-Test-p-Value" src=3D"h=
ttps://numiqo.com/assets/tutorial/Friedman/Friedman-Test-p-Value.png">
<p>
  At this point we can read the critical Chi<sup>2</sup> value in the criti=
cal values
  table. For this we take the predefined significance level, let's say it i=
s 0.05 and the
  number of degrees of freedom. We can read that the critical Chi<sup>2</su=
p> value is
  5.99. This is greater than our calculated value. Thus, the null hypothesi=
s is not
  rejected and based on this data, there is no difference between the respo=
nsiveness at
  the different time points. If the calculated Chi<sup>2</sup> value were g=
reater than the
  critical one, we would reject the null hypothesis.
</p>

<h2>Calculate Friedman test with numiqo</h2>

<p>
  For the calculation of the Friedman test you can simply use numiqo. To do=
 this, simply
  go to the
  <a routerlink=3D"/statistics-calculator/hypothesis-test/friedman-test-cal=
culator" href=3D"https://numiqo.com/statistics-calculator/hypothesis-test/f=
riedman-test-calculator">Friedman test calculator</a>
  on numiqo.com and copy your own data into the table.
</p>

<img alt=3D"Friedman-Test-Calculate-Online" title=3D"Friedman-Test-Calculat=
e-Online" src=3D"https://numiqo.com/assets/tutorial/Friedman/Friedman-Test-=
Calculate-Online.png">

<p>Now we get the results for the Friedman test.</p>
<img alt=3D"Friedman-Test-Results" title=3D"Friedman-Test-Results" src=3D"h=
ttps://numiqo.com/assets/tutorial/Friedman/Friedman-Test-Results.png">

<p>
  First you get the
  <a routerlink=3D"/tutorial/descriptive-inferential-statistics" href=3D"ht=
tps://numiqo.com/tutorial/descriptive-inferential-statistics">descriptive s=
tatistics</a>.
  Then you can read the p-value. If you don't know exactly how to interpret=
 the p-value,
  you can simply look at the interpretation in words. A Friedman test showe=
d that there is
  no significant difference between the variables. Chi<sup>2</sup> =3D 2.57=
, p =3D 0.276
</p>

<p>
  If your p-value is greater than your set significance level, then your nu=
ll hypothesis
  is not rejected. The null hypothesis is that there is no difference betwe=
en the groups.
  Usually, a significance level of 0.05 is used, so this p-value is greater=
.
</p>

<h2>Post-Hoc Test</h2>
<p>
  In addition, numiqo provides you the post-hoc test. If your p-value is sm=
aller than 0.05
  you can examine here which of the groups really differ!
</p>
<img alt=3D"Friedman-Test-Post-Hoc-Test" title=3D"Friedman-Test-Post-Hoc-Te=
